He distinguished himself by his successful expeditions against the Britons os CornwalL and the neighbouring states ofKent‚ Mercia, and Sussex, which had again assumed for a time a feeble independence. In the year 726, he suffered his picus disposition to get the better of his ambition as a Monarch, and, quitting his throne, departed to Rome, on what was at that time considered a holy pilgrimage. Here he embraced the monastic lise, and finally died, leaving behind him a name which is still preserved by tradition in the county os Somerset. His wife Ethelberga followed the example of ber husband, and became a nun in the Abbey of Berking.
